            "title": "Chapter 24 The theory of optimal taxation",
            "abstract": "This chapter discusses that the central element in the theory of optimal taxation is information. Optimal tax theory began with Ramsey, who solved the problem of raising revenue by commodity taxes from a single consume. It has been assumed that lump-sum taxation, as it happens quite unnecessarily, looks at optimal pricing by public enterprises subject to a budget constraint. Work on discount rates for public investment during the sixties often implicitly assumed imperfections, such as absence of lump-sum taxation. Many-consumer economy has been introduced without lump-sum taxes, stated, and proved the efficiency theorem. The chapter provides a discussion of existence and a case where the optimum can be obtained explicitly. The treatment of lump-sum taxation as based on individual information is related to the work on signaling and screening. A special case of nonlinear taxation, with extensive results and numerical calculations, has also been discussed in the chapter.",
